# UI Style and Theming Rule

CSS must produce a clean, professional visual design as the default experience.

## Style quality requirements

- Maintain consistent spacing, typography, and visual hierarchy.
- Keep component styles coherent and avoid ad-hoc one-off visual behavior.
- Preserve readability, contrast, and interaction clarity for common states (default/hover/active/disabled/focus).

## User style adaptation requirements

- Build styles so user adaptation can be added cleanly (theme tokens, CSS custom properties, or equivalent).
- Keep style decisions configurable through explicit theme variables, not scattered hard-coded values.
- Define clear extension points for future user-selected themes/modes without breaking defaults.

## Delivery checklist (substantial UI/CSS changes)

- Confirm the default look remains clean and professional.
- Confirm new styles are compatible with planned user adaptation points.
- Update public style/theming documentation when style APIs or tokens change.
